The paper deals with the problem of inferring centrality rankings of nodes in a network solely from nodal observations, which can be modeled as graph signals. This falls under the broad area of network analysis and inference, which is covered by several sub-categories in arXiv CS. 

cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is the most likely sub-category, as the paper deals with network analysis and inference, which is a core topic in social and information networks. 

cs.SD (Sound) is also a likely sub-category, as the paper uses the concept of graph signals to model nodal observations, which is a topic that has applications in sound processing. 

cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) is another possible sub-category, as the paper deals with network analysis and inference, which is a core topic in networking and internet architecture. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is a possible sub-category, as the paper proposes a spectral algorithm to estimate the leading eigenvector of the associated adjacency matrix, which is a common technique in machine learning. 

cs.IT (Information Theory) is another possible sub-category, as the paper provides a finite rate performance analysis of the algorithm, which is a topic that has applications in information theory.
